Contrary to what happens in Canada, the American states are responsible for the organization of federal elections in the United States.
And along the same lines, a majority of American governments enacted, as of 2009, new laws that made the registration or voting process difficult.
This phenomenon has spread after the November 2010 elections, which saw the increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
Consequently, in 2011, 180 bills were introduced that restricted the exercise of voting rights in 41 states.
New electoral laws require voters to present an identity document with a photograph, in addition to proof of American citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as a voter on the day of the count, and remove citizens with criminal records from voting.
Before the 2006 elections, no American state required voters to present a photo ID.
The State of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The United States Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of Indiana law in 2008.
For this reason, the Republican authorities were quick to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to bear in mind that, contrary to what happens in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as a Social Security card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have a photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 do not have an identity document with these characteristics.
But, often, obtaining the required identity document costs more than a hundred dollars.
As a result, the new restrictions disproportionately affect youth, minorities and people with low incomes.
Indeed, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people who earn less than $ 35,000 a year, 18% of citizens over 65 years of age and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years old do not have An identity document with a photograph.
And there are still more.
In many states, students, the voters who vote the most for Democratic candidates, cannot use the photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, those same states authorize members of fishing or hunting clubs who usually vote for Republican parties to use the documents issued by those clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to file such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws that require voters to prove that they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit the Hispanic vote.
It appears that two out of every three Hispanic voters support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, Republican lawmakers in 2011 supported certain laws that abolished voter registration on the same day as the ballot in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create a support service for voters who wanted to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general elections, voter registration drives contributed to the registration of around 10 million citizens.
Actions taken since 2009 caused the new voter registration rate to drop in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers adopted laws in five other states that favored shortening the early voting period.
For example, in the 2008 Florida elections, 33% of early voters were African-American, while early voters represented no more than 13% of the state&#39;s voters.
In the case of Hispanics, it was exactly the same.
They do not represent more than 11% of voters, which is equivalent to 24% of citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, who represent 76% of the electorate, represent no more than 46% of citizens who vote early.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have fervently opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
In this sense, the Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The United States Attorney&#39;s Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
It was possible, in part, to limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states adopted the law requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of voting rights in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been passed, since it is clear that they are intended to influence the 2012 results in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that have adopted such laws represent 171 of the 270 votes required in the electoral college to achieve the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty whether these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
One thing is certain: those new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
