The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson caused quite a stir last summer, and for good reason.
It is believed, in effect, that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
What&#39;s more, it is the particle whose existence the Standard Model predicted: our best or &quot;least bad&quot; explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists it is not entirely clear that it is the Higgs.
We know without a doubt that a new particle exists and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress held in Kyoto seem to confirm that it is, although more data is still missing to be completely sure.
In any case, we assume that it is Higgs, since the chances of being wrong seem small. We will see what it is about.
There is, in this great world, a generalized and inescapable law that implies that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to break that rule and don&#39;t try too hard, because you will end up hurting yourself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics: the Pauli exclusion principle, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same &quot;quantum state&quot;; a &quot;state&quot; that consists, roughly, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we meet the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey the Pauli principle.
And on the other are the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means that they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the Berkeley Laboratories&#39; The Particle Adventure website, which, by the way, is extraordinary, bosons are divided into two groups: mesons, which we will not talk about here, and &quot;force particles&quot;, by which large forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, it should be emphasized here, are not the exotic critters we might believe.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or the &quot;particle of light&quot; that acts as a &quot;messenger&quot; of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it &quot;messes up&quot; the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a bit like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this &quot;disorder&quot; an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing more than a photon; that is, one of the &quot;force-carrying&quot; bosons.
More stable field
The same happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be &quot;disordered&quot; for this boson to appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it, it is necessary to reach extremely high energies, a bit as if it were an icy pond in which only a thick rock could slide across the surface.
That is why it takes a huge particle accelerator like CERN&#39;s (the large hadron collider is a 27 km circumference ring!) To achieve such energy levels.
The electromagnetic field analogy is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles or all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others don&#39;t: a piece of paper, for example, will never stick to a fridge by itself.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way), do not.
Now, what &quot;can all this research contribute&quot;? Asks Mrs. Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between MS observations and predictions.
For their part, many fervently want to meet, as the slightest difference could open a door to a &quot;new physics&quot; that plugs certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has enormous shortcomings, as it does not propose any explanation related to gravity (oops!) Or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter in the Universe (oops!).
But we have not found such differences at CERN so far.
Repercussions
The repercussions of such research on our day-to-day lives are difficult to predict, but we do not think we are wrong in saying that it will not have any.
Just so you see: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of lasers in labs were not at all suspicious of the revolution their work would bring about.
They glimpsed the scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as the physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962, said, at first the laser was rather considered a &quot;laboratory apparatus&quot;.
Imagine ...
And in addition, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the investigation.
For example, Willard Boyle himself made a light collector in 1969 in the course of his research on optics.
Although it was not at all his original intention, this sensor now serves as an &quot;eye&quot; for all digital devices in the world, earning him the Nobel Prize in physics in 2009.
That does not mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC necessarily want to transform our lives, but that you never know ...
