Quite the opposite of current currency exchanges, based on central banks, identified transactions and processing charges between the parties.
Furthermore, as is often the case in technology, the political vision is palpable: the conviction that the current monetary system, made up of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is simultaneously a virtual currency convertible to dollars, euros, etc. and a secure exchange protocol in the manner of BitTorrent, which allows peer-to-peer file sharing.
Nearly 200,000 transactions have been registered thanks to 15,000 computers on the network.
And about a thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as a form of payment.
The price of bitcoin, after having reached the peak of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to 2 dollars five months later, before today returning to around ten dollars (the prices are registered on the bitcoincharts page .com).
It is not at all impressive when compared to world changes in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) took an interest in him in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
In it, bitcoin was described as &quot;the most successful virtual currency,&quot; &quot;competing with the dollar or the euro,&quot; and &quot;similar to conventional currencies.&quot;
Bitcoin differs from other systems with types of virtual currencies such as &quot;credits&quot;, used to advance in a video game and that can be won by playing or can be bought (and sometimes even redeemed).
The social network Facebook also developed this type of system.
But in all exchanges a central authority controls and deals with the changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously ledgers, verifiers, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually done between two electronic addresses in the form of email.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically through a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoin changes are recorded in the public account book, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key milestone is writing that new transaction in that book.
This passes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge thrown at the computers and the winner, a kind of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a file slicing phase, that is, the transformation of a large file into a shorter and unique numerical footprint.
Computers &quot;catch&quot; the new transaction and add a number before &quot;slicing&quot; the set.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular fingerprint (plus leading zeros).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to commit fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept one of the two transactions as valid; the other would be orphaned, since they both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge gets 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is divided in two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to one hundred millionth, which leaves a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in computing power.
The life of the network already has its ups and downs.
Websites offering services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins on deposit stolen.
&quot;The failure used does not affect the same protocol,&quot; says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real currency payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the possibilities of money laundering thanks to this anonymous service.
But cash has the same flaw.
Big players like Wikipedia reject payments of this type.
Others, like the Wordpress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, from the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the ledger and showed that about 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November the &quot;giant sales&quot; were launched.
&quot;$ 30,000 was exchanged,&quot; rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which turns bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogical book on this currency, believes a lot in the potential of this technology as well as in the network of transactions.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which are therefore cheaper.
The bearer also manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set up in stores, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
It is enough for them to supply an address that a phone can &quot;photograph and recognize&quot;, says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement of revision of the hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
&quot;It will take a while for Bitcoin to take hold, but in 2013 there could be a change,&quot; he predicts.
On the other hand, in its report the ECB plans to revalue the various risks, now considered high, should this currency be successful.
