The subject of augmented reality, so popular among fans of modern technologies, is lately perceived normally mainly through the prism of special glasses.
In early summer, Google demonstrated a model in motion at its annual conference and later, in November, it emerged that Microsoft had also filed an application to claim the corresponding patent.
However, from a conversation with the head of the 3D interactive technology group in Microsoft&#39;s Cambridge laboratory, Izadi Sharamom, it was elucidated that for the scientists of that company, the glasses already belonged to a past stage.
They are drawn to the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in midair with bare hands and creating open virtual spaces.
- Please, in general terms, what is the object of study of your research group?
- We are dedicated to human-computer interaction, but we also try to expand the limits of this interaction.
For now humanity in its great mass has been trapped in the stage of working with the pixels of the flat screen, sometimes you touch it with your finger.
But we want to look 5-10 years ahead and guess the cardinal changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and the Kinect sensors represent a step forward and today no Xbox is sold without the Kinect, since everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What else does the future hold?
- Although the Kinect has brought interaction to the physical level, much of it still happens on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information has improved (the system receives more data), and the output is still not very good.
We are trying to change this, we work on truly three-dimensional display systems, based on different technologies, including design.
The world of computing must be liberated from ours, the physical world, making it more tangible.
For this, however, it is necessary to recognize not only the user, but also the surrounding space.
Then we can complete the real world with virtual objects in a more comfortable way.
First of all, to hell with those silly virtual reality headsets!
- What do you think about voice control?
A very popular detail, but don&#39;t you think they are overestimating it?
- Of course, it cannot be considered a panacea, the privacy issue remains to be resolved, since we do not always want others to find out about our actions and intentions.
In fact, all types of computer interaction are good, but each in its own field.
For example, for the control of devices in public places, we had a project in which we think in gestures, but not in loose movements, but shorter.
In addition, the gestures were captured not by the device&#39;s camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movement of bones and muscles.
For now it is very large, but in theory it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But, in general, the future is for a combined type of control, for example gesture + voice.
- How is that?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass you this can of soda?
You will speak and show it at the same time.
- Usually I just talk.
- Oh, that is going to be very difficult to recognize.
- In other words, do you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or cannot do at the moment?
- Not necessarily, but it is a mutual approach.
I think that in the near future we will have to work mainly on the design of new types of sensors that can accurately determine the reactions of the person.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, as they provide good depth resolution, which is very important.
- If we talk about your work with the Xbox Kinect sensors, what complaints do you have about modern cameras?
Are you lacking resolution, depth, or something else?
- In principle, the current generation is what can be the beginning of our work with three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be nice to get 8 megapixels at 1000 fps.
But the question is not in the megapixels, but in the quality of the matrix and in the depth.
From this last point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us; this gives more work to algorithm designers.
In other words, we have to remember not only the resolution in the X and Y axes, but also in Z.
Speed is also important, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic and the current 30 fps are really scarce, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche from our lab in Redmond made a contact sensor with adjustable processing delay of 1 to 100 ms and it is worth mentioning that modern mass-produced sensors are closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands to what extent this affects human-machine interaction.
An equivalent of such a device would be very useful for my work, but one that does not require contact so that the frames per second are more.
- And is it not necessary to increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect now has three &quot;cameras&quot;, one of which is in fact the emitter of infrared rays and the second the receiver of the reflected signal.
But the third camera is actually a simple visible tuning fork sensor.
This is not used to determine the depth of the object.
Potentially more cameras could solve the problem ...
Or on the contrary, increase it and increase the required amount of calculations.
It would be nice to create a flexible Kinect analog, play around with the camera placement curvature, and see how this would help determine the three-dimensional position.
- From what I remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, has not presented its glasses to the public.
