- Let&#39;s imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only for Tony Stark from the movie &quot;Iron Man&quot;, but also for any simple mortal.
There is a problem with this idea that critics often point out: there is no tactile feedback!
The hands feel nothing!
What responses does your group prepare for this challenge?
- In my lectures I often say that augmented reality is the seventh irruption in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth could well be the addition of tactile sensations.
Meanwhile, one of the most interesting tricks is the use of the second hand as a support for the image.
It registers the touch perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are truly oriented to bring tangibility to these &quot;images in the air&quot;. For example, the interference of several ultrasonic rays directed at a specific point where the finger is located gives a sensation similar to what one feels if someone were blowing into the fingertips, but that sensation is still very weak.
There are also wrist bracelets that influence the nerve endings of the fingers, this also a promising direction.
- Have you tried to fool the brain?
Make him think that he feels what he seems like he should feel the moment he sees something?
- That&#39;s a good idea, we haven&#39;t tried it yet.
Here is another challenge that we will have to fight for a long time, how to make a person physically located in a very small space believe that they are going to an open space, almost without end. We are also working on the idea of treadmills (not like those in gyms), mobile platforms, as well as giant balloons.
For now, tricking the brain is not so easy, you still have to work for many years.
That is what makes working with virtual reality attractive for researchers, that many things are in a state of total conception.
