Head of NKÚ: The inspection of the &quot;švarc&quot; system has not found the guilty politician
When it comes to public awards, the Czech Republic has good inspectors and quality legislation, although enforcement is lacking.
This is stated by Miloslav Kala, vice president of the Supreme Control Office (NKÚ) in an interview for Aktuálně.cz.
&quot;The law will never be perfect&quot;, but its application must be correct. &quot;This is, in my opinion, what we lack&quot;, this is how he describes the current situation.
The joint checks of the Czech and German inspectors also reach similar conclusions.
As an example of incorrect practice, he mentions Petr Nečas&#39;s attitude towards the system of being autonomous only on paper, which is known as the &quot;švarc&quot; system.
The prime minister recently said that the ODS (Civic Democratic Party) would not bother businessmen with inspectors. So is it forbidden or allowed?
&quot;The law must be regulated in some way and if it prohibits something, in that case, not even the president of the government can prevent the performance of the office that has the obligation to carry out said controls or demand obligations,&quot; Kala states.
At the meeting of the control commission in the Congress of Deputies, you spoke of the common project between the Czech and German teams, in the framework of which the legislation regarding public awards in both countries was compared.
What exactly?
This is a parallel control that we started to carry out about two years ago.
Said in a simplified way: European legislation regulates how public awards should be organized, this is followed by the legislation in force in each country and, later, by the practice itself.
We have put it all together and, although the control has not finished yet, we have obtained very interesting differences. Generally, the legislation of our country is &quot;stricter and more complete&quot;, however, the concrete practice in some parameters is better in Germany.
Therefore, it is confirmed that it is not enough to incorporate increasingly strict rules, but that it is necessary to concentrate on the application of the law itself.
What can this project actually contribute? What do you think are the conclusions?
Precisely a common control of this type could help us to stop investing efforts in the concretion of the laws, the reduction and the improvement of the limits, although this does not have such a positive impact.
Saving economics means getting a suitable thing at a reasonable price (which does not always mean that the price is the lowest) in order to avoid enrichment and, in the long run, criminal actions.
But the fact of reducing the limit of the awards does not mean that we are going to achieve it.
Perhaps because the system is saturated with so much &quot;paperwork&quot; that those who want to find fault with the system will be able to do so more easily than if the limits were kept as high as they are now.
You talk about the problems of our country with the transfer of the legislation that regulates the practice of public awards.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is it an office similar to our NKÚ or is it organized in a different way?
As for the offices, such as the NKÚ, the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Accounts) operates there, with an organization similar to ours, with a college as well, the only thing is that in your case it is structured in a somewhat different way, but in principle both offices evolve in parallel.
Also the powers are to some extent analogous, however, as long as Germany has a federal organization, the courts of accounts are even at this level. In this respect it differs slightly from our system.
The Federal Court of Accounts (BRH) can only control federal money, what we here call state funds.
Public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, there in Germany, are controlled by the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
Generally, I wouldn&#39;t want to make a comparison without hard data. However, Germany is still a model in some respects, but it is not possible to pinpoint exactly where it is better.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of the inspectors?
Surely not, but, I repeat, I do not like to make such comparisons.
It goes without saying that even those countries that we take as a model face a great number of problems.
If not, it would be of no benefit to you to collaborate with our office, would you not?
Regarding the legislation of our country, what did the amendment to the law on public awards mean for your Office? Is its incidence manifested in some way?
Taking into account that the validity period of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been manifested in the control proceedings.
Since we carry out ex post controls, a certain delay is necessary.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparing future controls: we have started a new tool for &quot;detecting non-economic risks&quot;, through which we have passed almost 14,000 public awards, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, since the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process and the like are rectified.
Do you consider that the approval of this law is beneficial or that, rather, it represents a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I believe that this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope that it is.
The problem that can arise is that the regulations &quot;become tougher&quot; and that it is impossible to comply with them.
Already with the previous regulations, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of the regional operating programs of the regional council), and each law not respected in the matter of public awards meant the violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense then to toughen the law in this way?
I think not this way.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or take advantage of it and not punish those who commit a formal failure, which has no bearing on decision-making.
Such a system will only create more bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We will see where this initiated path takes us.
The prime minister recently stated that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called švarc system, referring to being autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the švarc &quot;system forbidden or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits something, then not even the prime minister of the government can prevent the action of the Office that has the obligation to carry out such controls and demand obligations.
You can say: &quot;We change the law and we allow it,&quot; but you cannot say that we will do nothing.
In the law on public awards, the regulations are quite strict as to the way in which one must act formally. And this is how it should be to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate with the best offer is excluded for not meeting the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This is, in my opinion, what we lack.
