Šimon Ornest: In our concerts we want to accumulate positive energy
It is said that in a little less than a month the end of the world will come, what do you think about it?
It is just one of many other alarmist news that we like to cling to.
The music group The Tap Tap rather likes to make jokes about this and we like to say that we are the only music group in the world that manages to gather enough positive energy to postpone the end of the world or to prevent it.
Also, in December you organize a really original project: three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you explain it to our readers?
This is a state charity event that we have been planning for two years.
We decided to take advantage of the marketing potential of the end of the Mayan calendar announced for December 21 at 11:10 in the morning.
The day before, on December 20 at 9:00 p.m., we will organize 3 simultaneous concerts in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end at approximately the same time that the Mayan calendar ends on the island of Kiribati, in the Pacific Ocean, 12 hours ahead of our time zone.
Who came up with this idea?
Initially it was my idea, then we forged the project all together with our designer Honza Augusta.
In addition to wanting to gather enough positive energy and avoid the end of the world, we also want to reflect, together with society, on the state in which we will leave the world to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar we have also created a unique collection of articles: boots, t-shirts, bags and original key rings against the end of the world that can be purchased at www.e-tap.cz, another way of supporting us.
The group The Tap Tap, along with other interpreters, also sang the so-called anthem against the end of the world, which is entitled &quot;End of the world, canceled.&quot;
It is currently very popular on YouTube, will you be able to hear it at benefit concerts?
Of course I do, and it will be just the last, well, as long as everything goes well and the world does not end ...
It will be sung by all the performers at the same time in all three concerts.
The hymns will be linked together simultaneously thanks to the special live broadcast on Czech Television.
Tomáš Hanák has written the lyrics for this song and plays the title role of Jesus in the video clip, where Xindl X also sings ...
How did this collaboration come about?
We even work together with other personalities from the Czech cultural scene, apart from organizing many charity events and concerts ...
We do our best to participate in this project.
Most of them have been shown to be interested and have fun working with us.
What will the money raised at the concerts against the end of the world go to?
To equipping the barrier-free education center Studeo, which we have completed in its sixth consecutive year with the civil association Tap in Jedličkův ústav.
The pupils of the Jedličkův ústav school are regularly visited by teachers with whom they carry out fun and interesting activities.
The students do not have sufficient financial means to pay the teachers and we make an effort to make it possible.
As part of the completion of the works in Jedličkův ústav, there will be a separate building to which we will move with this project.
In each concert several groups and interpreters act.
Which are the selection criteria?
We try to create a program that is attractive to all generations, including children.
For example, in Prague Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý will perform.
For more detailed information, you can consult www.kpks.cz.
Do you have any other similar &quot;spectacular action&quot; planned in the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the Pražské jaro festival, so here we will surely prepare an attractive program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to play at the Bohemian National Hall in New York and I personally, taking advantage of the fact that we are in the United States, I would like to complete it with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not exactly minimalist, so far you have performed for example in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is, however, a group made up of people with disabilities.
How is the logistics and organization of these trips?
It is not as difficult as it may seem at first glance.
There are five members in an electric wheelchair, the chairs must travel in the luggage compartment and we also carry a lot of weight, the boxes with the instruments ...
However, so far we have managed well. ČSA and British Airways were perfectly prepared, which never ceases to amaze me.
Even in Moscow, where we have recently returned, everything went smoothly.
Thanks to the trips abroad you can compare the different attitudes of society towards the disabled and other aspects.
What have you come across so far?
In Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities, everything works better than here; in Russia we have witnessed that, in the east, there is a long way to go.
Unlike Prague, Moscow is full of barriers, there it is still rare for a person to travel alone through the city center in an electric wheelchair.
Something as common as it is, for example, giving preference to someone in a wheelchair in the elevator, it is not there.
Fortunately, a civil association has been created that strives to thematize the problems of people with disabilities.
In what respects should we take the example of more advanced countries?
There are many aspects in which we are behind ...
But it is important to mention that the improvement and improvement of the situation always depends on the people it directly affects.
In London and Madrid it is very normal for people with a serious disability to travel on their own in public and can go to the service, to the museum, wherever they want ...
But it is not very common for a large number of people with disabilities to participate in social life actively, in this regard, with The Tap Tap, we are a little ahead!
A respectful or barrier-free society is one thing, but when the time comes when eminent athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers emerge, everything will really start to change.
So far, they are isolated cases of people who have great willpower.
The group The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but if we look back a few years, what led you to form the group in 1998?
I entered Jedličkův ústav as an educator, where I had a lot of young people around me who wanted to dedicate themselves to something.
And since I am a musician, I play, among others, the saxophone, I founded an amateur group with a co-worker.
And over time, as our moderator Láďa Angelovič says, it got a bit out of hand (laughs).
However, the popularity did not arrive until these last years, or am I wrong?
It is true that connecting with famous singers and actively working to promote the group helped us a lot.
We conclude that work that is not seen is as if it did not exist.
Thanks to the aid of the European Union, we can also afford quality teachers, equipment, etc.
Did you intend to go that far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning I saw the potential that there was, that something can be done differently.
Show business is full of things that resemble each other.
It is logical, in its own way, everything new is welcomed with caution and takes a long time to be accepted.
There are few extraordinary things, but I dare say The Tap Tap is one of them.
The impression of someone who sees us for the first time is clearly compassion, it is a natural reaction ...
But compassion is totally superfluous because people with disabilities are not abandoned beings who suffer and for whom we should have compassion.
There are people who are able to live a full life and develop, provided, of course, that they have the necessary means.
I always say that if something goes well for people with disabilities, then it is not only progress for them, but for the whole of society.
Did the fact that you are a demanding boss, as many people describe you, help?
If we want to do quality work, we have to be rigorous in many aspects and demand a certain discipline.
I think it is completely normal.
Some people arrive with a romantic vision and with their heads in the clouds and when they find out that they have to attend two days to rehearse, go to the preparatory test and spend a lot of time traveling and at concerts, the initial euphoria quickly leaves them.
But this is how it works everywhere, in every group that wants to work and achieve something.
Currently the group The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of them were already in the beginning of 1998?
Only one: Láďa Angelovič.
We are an open group, people come and go, it can&#39;t be helped.
