Poland and the cosmos.
At last week&#39;s meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency countries, Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of ESA. It is the second ESA member country of the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on November 12, 2008).
Poland began an intensive collaboration with ESA in 1994 and in subsequent years participated in the agency&#39;s project commission.
However, Poland&#39;s path to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already involved in space flights before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, A. Šternfeld&#39;s lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory in which, on December 6, 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study &quot;Introduction to Cosmonautics&quot;.
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience indifferent and, years later, Šternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his &quot;Introduction to Cosmonautics&quot;.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned earlier, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, he was known throughout the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named after him.
As early as 1925, a dresine was built in Poland that was to be fitted with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is unknown and the details of the project are not known.
It is not clear whether the rocket was to be used for starting the dray or for braking it.
The information on this dresine is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
From the year 1933 the Polish artillery began to dedicate itself to missiles.
The research was funded by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it is clear that the investigation reached the stage of practical tests.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the investigation was halted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric hunting missile designed by the engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press and the following year the study &quot;Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza&quot;, by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki, was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was in charge of all projects of missile techniques for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the start of the war.
Other studies devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 issue of Problemy magazine, the society was referred to for the first time with four very lengthy articles devoted to astronautics.
In one of them, by prof. M. Subotowicze, proposed the creation of a society that would be dedicated to cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with prospects for the future.
From the beginning of 1956 the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) aspired to be part of the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in the autumn of that same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first PTA president, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA had a significant role in the development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) probe rocket, which was a success and became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and was first launched on October 10, 1958.
The rocket had an apogee of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg in weight.
Later, construction of the RM-1A version was completed, and in the summer of 1959, aerial testing of the two-stage RM-2 rockets began in the Błędów desert.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of rocket in development was to be the subject of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was going to have an apogee of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the high wind.
However, in 1962 the works were suspended.
The successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during the years 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which were differentiated from each other by the space available for scientific devices.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for the volume was 0.4 liters, in the Meteor-1B it was 0.34 liters and in the Meteor-1C it was 0.62 liters.
The peak in all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, the first aerial tests of which began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km high.
Later the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also necessary to mention Poland&#39;s entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national COSPAR committee two years later.
In the framework of the Interkosmos program, Poland joined the cosmic space research on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimír Remek.
Suspending the social work law is not the solution.
Last week the constitutional court suspended the social work law.
The resolution sparked a heated discussion in society.
Of course, it will be interesting to examine the existing problems from a broader point of view.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalized world, are based on the principle of greater economic competition and less regulation.
Consequently, this means that different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the principle of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, together with unbridled financial speculation.
The effect of large differences in labor cost (of wages) produces economic stress.
Under this concept, it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, by importing cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and for this &quot;causes a drop&quot; in the price of the competitor in order to take over most of the market and, therefore, This way, you increase your profit margin.
On a large scale it means, for most entrepreneurs, moving production abroad, buying there cheaper or disappearing. The result is high unemployment in those countries where the price of labor, compared to other economies, is higher.
Because private capital does not have any social responsibility and, therefore, is not responsible for the unemployment that this phenomenon generates, the social spending of the state necessarily grows.
All this situation fosters the total disinterest of businessmen to pay taxes and compensate for the economic and social damages that they have caused in their desire to obtain benefits.
The situation is universally so well known that it is not necessary to present concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create situations, in certain economies, in which the governments of those countries are forced to compete with the objective of artificially lowering the social level of their own population and thus attracting foreign capital to the country. country.
In other words, governments make private capital available to their own population regardless of social decline.
This is evident above all in the changes in the laws in force.
The objective is to force the population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially with regard to wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the financial obligation system in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other, through the restricted right of employees regarding labor rights.
The result is increasing poverty along with widening the gap between rich and poor.
For a number of years, there have been food delivery points in Germany for poor people who cannot support themselves with their own work.
The number of people who receive this type of aid already reaches one million.
Within the framework of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, a fairly frequent case occurs: people employed with a salary so low that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum essential to survive.
A scandal of this type related to the situation of the auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament was made public.
The savings measures of practically all the southern states of the EU lead, without a doubt, to the same situation. People, pressured by an abysmal decline in their social status, are forced to emigrate as in the 19th century or to live with a lousy salary on the edge of society, in the hope that one day private investment capital will arrive in the country.
Do you need to wonder where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, then poverty passes from one country to another or never comes, since Chinese, Indians, Brazilians, Turks, Moroccans, Egyptians or Africans continue to work for a tiny part of a European salary.
This also affects all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media claim ad nauseam that the state should not bring capital to the economy, that running the economy leads to its failure.
Private capital defends tooth and nail the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by meddling in control.
Next, it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence the political march with its egoism and, therefore, the entire state.
In this case the answer is clearly yes.
The proof is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and omnipresent, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation that manifests itself in the field of corruption, in mutual favors, in legislation that is practically reprehensible everywhere but is not punishable.
In Germany the situation is as follows: state ministries, lacking financial means, entrust the drafting of bills to private law firms, which are often linked to industry.
These kinds of bills are later passed in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
In this way, all power does not emanate from the people, as announced in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from strong financial groups that represent their own interests.
