The failure in Iran was a decisive factor in Jimmy Carter&#39;s defeat to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film &quot;Argo&quot; by the director and actor Ben Affleck thematizes an episode of this story, which was a small success for America.
Shortly before occupying the embassy, six employees escaped from the building.
After a complicated journey, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian embassy.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, for which an extravagant story helped an extravagant point: they left with Canadian passports, as members of the film team that was examining the location in the country for the filming of a science fiction blockbuster .
Combination of genres
The plan drawn up by &quot;exfiltration&quot; expert Toni Mendez required Hollywood&#39;s collaboration.
To make the lie appear true, the film project was written about in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictional production company even had a real office.
The details about the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck&#39;s movie is a unique combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called &quot;caper movie&quot;, the story of an episode that went well, a hoax (an example could be the Ocean&#39;s Eleven series).
Moods are combined in the film. We find on the one hand well-documented sequences from Tehran. In the sequence of credits, emblematic photographs of the time of the events are shown, which were captured in the same way in the film; there are not many differences in this regard.
On the other, typical Hollywood scenes somewhat lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And also, scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions: men in suits analyzing the situation at the negotiating table, in the corridors of the office, on the phone ...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The teased actor has become a respectable director and his acting has ceased to be the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is her third feature film, after &quot;Goodbye little one, Goodbye&quot; (2007) and the thriller &quot;The Town. City of thieves&quot; (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck&#39;s first film in which the action does not take place in the city of Boston, where he grew up.
Also, the sensitivity of capturing the atmosphere of the place was a characteristic that placed the directors of old films above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck proves it in Argo, where Tehran is &quot;filmed&quot; in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of the real events. The introductory sequence of the seizure of the embassy is impressive for its synoptic capacity that, at the same time, conveys the emotion of bewilderment and lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, the story takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the impostor team in the Tehran bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story doesn&#39;t offer much in the cinematic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
And it manages quite well. Sometimes it adds something to reality: everything does not turn out so gracefully here (the scene of the crisis looming at the Tehran airport, the diversion of a call to America and the unbridled search on its trail all turn into madness ).
Argo&#39;s weakness is the lack of control that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more space and they are by no means the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck&#39;s film loses a bit of dramatic edge, but it is a film that can be followed with moderate interest, appreciating its realization and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 70s.
But for it to collapse, that will be difficult.
As an evocation of a true story and as proof of how exaggerated secret services notions of omnipresence and omniscience can be, it is enough.
