Szabo: &quot;The Germans must play a more leading role&quot;
Germany has abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-Europe relations, this puts Berlin in a rather tricky diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier in the week, Germany hinted that it would vote against the proposal to grant the Palestinian territories UN observer state status.
However, finally Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, due to the special relationship that binds the country to Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time I don&#39;t think he supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising that took place in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position when important international issues are at stake?
Yes that&#39;s how it is.
This is because at the moment it is reorienting its foreign policy, away from a policy led, so to speak, by the United States and towards a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
Therefore, the Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to doing so.
I think they are still working out what their role will be, but they have already started on the path to a &quot;normal&quot; foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to that of countries like France or Great Britain.
What does a &quot;normal&quot; foreign policy mean concretely from the German point of view?
It is a policy that, when it comes to national interests, is willing to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy finds a strong motivation in economic policy, that is, in exports and in its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are to some extent different from those of other great powers and for this reason Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position taken on the conflict in the Middle East and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
For this reason, she must be careful not to alienate herself from Arab public opinion or from Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I would not give it that much importance since it is not a totally one-sided relationship.
However, they do play a key role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the US by abstaining from voting on important decisions such as the vote on Palestine?
I think that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German position is highly understood.
For this reason, I do not believe that there has been such a drastic break as in the case of Libya.
Perhaps in this way Germany has managed to earn a certain respect.
At the end of the day, all this has only shown that it is a country that is taken seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
In Europe there are different opinions about the Palestinian initiative.
Instead, the US has been clearly in favor of a veto.
Is there a disparity of opinion between the US and many European nations?
These disparities have always existed because of American domestic politics.
I think the Obama administration secretly shows a great understanding of the European position.
But, because of the political situation here, it is clear that the government cannot publicly defend that position.
I think that the true disparity of opinion is not really the size that is attributed to it.
If we analyze the relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, we see that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about the policy he is developing.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of its main partners in the EU, on the other?
I think that is precisely what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course it would be a bit easier for the Germans if there was a coherent and homogeneous European policy, but this is not the case.
Therefore, they do not have the possibility of being part of a higher entity, but must promote things from their own position.
That is precisely what they are doing now with the euro.
I believe that in future Germany will take a leading role in forcing Europe to adopt a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, either simply because of its relationship with Israel.
This has always been a tricky subject.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they must play the role of an independent figure.
Does Germany see itself in the role of a major international actor? Does Germany really want to take a leading role?
Or is it still difficult for you to accept that leadership?
Germany has not gotten used to it yet, it is always somewhat uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country is still struggling to play a bigger role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, we see that every time Germany positions itself as the main player, certain anti-German sentiments are unleashed.
This is not easy for the Germans.
This is an old problem and it is that nobody wants to be surrounded by enemy countries.
Seen in this light, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
You must show a receptive attitude towards different neighbors and opinions and that is not easy.
The influence of the USA in European politics diminishes more and more, but the EU does not fill that void at the moment, who is left then?
The Germans will have no choice but to assume a more leading role.
Even if they don&#39;t like it, find it unpleasant, or make them an even more unpopular people, c&#39;est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is Executive Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institution where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly discuss the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German politics, American foreign policy, and transatlantic relations.
&quot;Brand Protection&quot; in China: When Puma and Armani Suddenly Become Chinese Brands
Armani is a globally known brand and Polo Ralph Lauren as well.
But what is Armani Polo?
Behind this name there is a name that is officially registered in China but has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it is protected as long as the true eponyms do not file a lawsuit.
And even then it is not clear that they are going to agree.
&quot;Foreigners are finding it increasingly difficult to protect their trademarks in China,&quot; says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at the Taylor Wessing law firm specializing in protection rights violations in the Far East.
Every week a new case comes to my table.
Imitators simply add a couple of letters in order to register their trademarks.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and instead of Prada Prada-Kny is registered.
German companies also legally copy themselves in the same way, as has happened to the sporting goods manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a filing cabinet containing seats from the Beijing trademark office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company applied to register the Zegna DF Puma trademark, an artificial name also used by the Ermenegildo Zegna fashion house.
That the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is well known.
In large cities there are department stores with several floors dedicated exclusively to the sale of counterfeits.
However, the Pattloch cases are of a different nature. On behalf of his clients, he fights against the fact that the trademark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to profit from a name that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it &quot;Bang Ming Pai&quot; or companion brand.
The word has its origin in the Chinese term &quot;Bang Dakuan&quot;,
which refers to women who have &quot;caught&quot; a rich man.
Chinese authorities do not feel guilty
&quot;It&#39;s bad for business, you have to fight it,&quot; Pattloch demands.
&quot;The brand is leaking, the monopolistic position disappears and the damage suffered by the image is enormous.&quot;
The financial losses and the legal costs of the affected sectors are in the millions, especially in the case of emblematic luxury products.
According to data from the market analysis company CLSA, with a volume of 15,000 million euros per year, China is, in size, the third market for luxury goods and the one that grows the fastest.
However, achieving the cancellation of registrations of dubious legality in the trademark registry is complicated and also involves a lot of money.
The processes can take up to nine years and the outcome is uncertain.
Pattloch talks about cases in which the court dismissed a lawsuit because so much time had elapsed that the name that was the subject of the lawsuit had already become a &quot;market reality.&quot;
&quot;If the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even have to pay the plagiarist money because the process has damaged the plagiarist&#39;s brand in China,&quot; says Pattloch.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the best known cases have to do with graphic elements.
In 2009 Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that was recently taken over by German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
That is why today the Chinese can continue to use an emblem very similar to the Mercedes star.
Volvo&#39;s buyer, Geely, originally used a white and blue logo that was largely reminiscent of BMW; the matter was settled in court and Geely had to modify it.
Clothing manufacturer Lacoste lost in China to copycats from Hong Kong and Singapore whose logo depicted a crocodile looking in the opposite direction from the original.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
The CTMO trademark office in Beijing acknowledges that in 2010 they had difficulties due to a shortage of equipment and staffing.
Last year, however, &quot;the labor emergency situation returned to normal.&quot;
In this way, the number of unprocessed claim processes has been reduced by 22%.
Almost 57,000 of these cases were resolved, 75% more than the previous year.
However, 81,500 claims remain pending resolution.
Fighting this costs a lot of money
As is customary in China, the numbers are staggering.
Last year the CTMO registered more than 1.4 million applications for trademark protection, almost a third more than in 2010.
It would be a new record and means that China leads the list of new registrations worldwide for the tenth consecutive year, according to the trademark office.
It seems that this also occurs with the number of valid logos, a figure that amounts to 5.5 million in total.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan would have been pocketed in royalties.
In other words, this means that on average each registration costs 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Fighting this costs a lot of money, as the case of the German family business Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years the group has been fighting in court against a Chinese copycat.
While the Germans have succeeded in stopping the illegal manufacture of knockoff auto parts,
the copycat has managed to secure the Chinese rights to the Freudenberg trademark.
&quot;We ourselves have caused this situation because in Germany surnames are not protected,&quot; says Hanno Wentzler, Chairman and CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialties in Munich.
The CTMO trademark office also dismissed the appeal of the people from Munich.
In the next two instances they have agreed with Freudenberg, but the other side is still fighting today.
You have to be very careful
Now the case has reached the doors of the Superior Court of Justice, where it is still pending resolution.
Wentzler is confident that he will be able to resolve the issue favorably and praises the professionalism of the courts.
However, he also states that &quot;the procedure is extremely expensive, both in terms of money and time.&quot;
Internal costs are difficult to estimate; the corporate file has had to review files up to one hundred years old in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago Freudenberg offered the opposing party a &quot;six-figure sum in euros&quot; with the aim of reaching an amicable settlement, but to no avail.
&quot;This shows how much we care,&quot; says Wentzler.
The dangers lurking in the Far East even threaten to affect Europe,
specifically if imitators secure their rights to unprotected trademarks there.
Thus, a Chinese manufacturer tried to register the Freudenberg name for shoes and leather products in Germany.
The group has long since abandoned this commercial sphere, however it managed to prevent registration.
&quot;You have to be extremely careful,&quot; says Wentzler.
Both he and attorney Pattloch advise German companies to be extremely cautious when doing business with China.
It is not enough to trust international legislation on trademark rights, but what you have to do is &quot;also register in China everything that may be susceptible to protection&quot;, as Wentzler points out.
Otherwise, the theme can be much more expensive than a simple registration.
In fact, should Freudenberg lose the last round of his private battle, then he would have to pay the opposing party license fees in his own name, as Wentzler explains.
That or the segment in question would drive us out of the market.
World AIDS Day: Dance, Sing, Help
Imbongi choir rehearses in Heidelberg and AIDS orphans rejoice in Swaziland
The story of a bond capable of overcoming much more than 8,733 kilometers in distance.
First you start with the dance: cowboy boots, basketball shoes, heels and loafers look for the beat on the parquet floor, and they find it quickly.
One, two, three, four.
Only then do the voices of the singers slowly rise (alto, bass, tenor, and soprano), swirling, dulling, and following each other.
And Fiete Hopf, the 29-year-old director, threatens to almost go out of his mind as he tries to bring order with his energetic and gentle gestures.
It is Monday afternoon and in the music room of the Heidelberg Institute of Medical Psychology the Imbongi choir is rehearsing a new song.
The fifty singers have also arrived, between 23 and 69 years old, from the human geneticist to the householder.
&quot;Om&#39;Obani&quot; is not an easy piece, each voice of the choir has a different text and also in a barely known foreign language: Zulu, a language spoken by eleven million people in South Africa, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique and in some areas of Swaziland.
Help for self-help
According to an estimate by UNAIDS, the United Nations program to fight AIDS, worldwide there are approximately 34 million people infected with the HIV virus.
23.5 million of them live in southern Africa.
There are 245,000 AIDS orphans in Swaziland.
More than 40% of the population is already HIV positive.
The Voices for Africa association has found godparents in Germany for the 180 AIDS orphans in the town of Esitjeni.
Seventy of them attend high school.
For 15 or 20 euros a month you can sponsor a child.
This contribution will cover school tuition, uniform and guarantee you a hot meal a day at the Gogo Center.
Imbongi means &quot;storyteller&quot; or &quot;panegyricist&quot; in Zulu.
No one in this room can speak this Bantu language fluently, but they can sing.
For ten years this choir has been rehearsing songs in this soft foreign language that sometimes manages to transport them to their place of origin: southern Africa.
8,733 kilometers away in a straight line from Heidelberg, in the northeast of the kingdom of Swaziland, there is a town called Esitjeni that depends on the voices of this German choir.
Forty percent are infected
Approximately 2,000 people live there, some still in simple mud and straw huts, a large part of them are children.
More than 300 no longer have parents because they have succumbed to AIDS.
Esitjeni is a small example of what affects Swaziland: the highest AIDS infection rate and the lowest life expectancies in the world, according to Unicef.
The population does not approve of circumcision, a practice that has been shown to reduce the risk of infection by half.
More than 40% of Swazi people are carriers of the immunodeficiency virus, and dying in their early thirties has become common.
During a joint trip to Africa in the spring of 2005 the choir discovered this remote town, but what they saw above all were many children in the streets who lacked not only the protection of their parents, but the main thing: food, clothing and training.
Without a school degree, the chances in a poor country are more than slim.
At first it was only the private commitment of a few that made it possible for a child to go to school and enjoy a hot meal a day. All this for a few euros.
However, a year later the choir founded the association &quot;Voices for Africa&quot; which has since professionally cared for AIDS orphans in Esitjeni.
Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STDs include syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
The most common viral STDs are AIDS, human papillomavirus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Crabs and scabies are among the STDs transmitted by parasites.
What are the main affected groups?
Syphilis and gonorrhea occur more often in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four out of every five cases of syphilis recorded in Germany have their origin in sexual contact between men.
In the case of heterosexual adults, the most common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydia, trichomonas, human papillomavirus, candidiasis (fungus) and gonorrhea infections.
HIV infection among heterosexual adults in the country is relatively low; however, approximately 20% of new HIV infections are in this group.
Chlamydia infections are much more common among young people than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In our country, the human papilloma virus is also added to the most common diseases among youth.
How has the number of infections evolved?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are notifiable.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been on a downward trend since 2007.
In 2011, approximately 2,700 cases were registered.
This is one-tenth less than in the previous year.
What symptoms indicate that it is a venereal disease?
Infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort when urinating, discharge, abdominal pain, as well as blisters or warts.
They often do not cause pain or cause other symptoms and therefore go undetected.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but they do not offer one hundred percent protection.
Some pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted through infections by dirt and physical contact.
For this reason, experts recommend regular medical examinations, especially if you frequently change your sexual partner.
If diagnosed early, most STDs can be cured and any late consequences can be avoided.
Through collaborations, donations and, last but not least, the fees charged by the choir for their performances throughout Germany, they come to raise quite a bit of money.
&quot;In total we have already sent about 200,000 euros to Esitjeni,&quot; says proud Annette Lennartz, president of the association.
In Zodwa Dlamini village itself, a confident woman with leadership gifts manages the money sent from Germany.
She makes sure that the orphans find good accommodation, for example with one of the grandmothers.
The &quot;gogos&quot;, as older women are called in Zulu, are the pillars of the town.
Some of them have up to 14 orphans in their care, offer them a roof to live in and see that the children attend school every day on time and dressed in their uniforms.
Those who have no one are left under the protection of Khanyisile, a single woman who, like the two cooks who are in charge of cooking every day for more than 200 hungry children, receives a salary from the association.
In addition, &quot;Voices of Africa&quot; has started a sewing school, built two chicken coops and, in collaboration with the US health organization PSI, has succeeded in getting many of the villagers tested for HIV.
This is not something obvious, since, despite how evident this disease is throughout the country, it is not usually talked about openly.
A king with 14 wives
&quot;AIDS is an absolute taboo,&quot; says Annette Lennartz, &quot;because it has to do with sexuality.&quot;
Something strange in a country where the king officially has 14 wives.
The last absolute monarch of Black Africa, King Mswati III, is known for his opulent and opulent lifestyle.
Polygamy instead of democracy.
This not officially accepted way of life is largely responsible for the rapid spread that the HIV virus has experienced in recent decades.
But it is also due to the innumerable seasonal workers who travel the country from one place to another and who take it wherever they go.
According to Annette Lennartz, &quot;you can get free condoms on any street corner, but they are hardly used.
It&#39;s another culture, here they only accept skin-to-skin contact. &quot;
To foster cultural exchange, the Imbongi choir travels every two to three years through southern Africa singing songs that speak of melancholy, combative spirit, hope and confidence in the black race, songs that many in the southernmost tip of the African continent still They remember from the apartheid era.
A bus full of whites singing songs in a black language; So much recognition not only brings with it an excellent atmosphere and a lot of joy, but it has also managed to draw a couple of tears from the occasional rabid border soldier.
The trip always takes them to Esitjeni, where the singers visit sponsored children.
Although this small town hardly appears on maps, it is well known in the Ezulweni River Valley.
&quot;Come to Esitjeni, the light shines there,&quot; say the locals.
And after traveling the 8,733 kilometers in a straight line back to Heidelberg to the rehearsal rooms on Bergheimer Street packed with singers marking the pace, one realizes that it is also possible to see their light shine from there.
