In a constantly connected world, it&#39;s not so bad to get a little bored
During the Thanksgiving holidays this year, I unexpectedly had to spend five hours at an airport because the plane we were flying on suffered a mechanical problem and we had to wait for another plane to arrive.
So I had a lot of time to think about boredom.
I&#39;m not going to lie to you.
Spending half a day in an airport waiting for a flight to arrive is quite boring, even if you have the means to be entertained, such as books, magazines or iPhones, not to mention duty-free shops.
But more and more scholars and child development experts are praising the benefits of boredom.
According to them, it is okay that both we and our children get bored from time to time.
Being bored forces the brain to search for interesting options and may encourage creativity.
Since most of us are currently connected to this or that screen, we do not experience the benefits of boredom.
So should we take boredom in good spirits?
Yes.
And no.
But, we will talk about it later.
First, like many people, I assumed that, now that we have more time for leisure, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But, as stated by Peter Toohey, Professor of Greek and Roman History at the University of Calgary, in Canada, and author of the book &quot;Boredom: A Lively History&quot; published in 2011 by Yale University Press, it is not.
&quot;In fact, the history of boredom is very long,&quot; he says.
On the walls of Pompeii there are graffiti in Latin about boredom dating from the 1st century AD
We must also consider how we define boredom.
&quot;The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in many different ways,&quot; says John D. Eastwood, professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After reviewing published research and bringing the idea to a discussion group of 100, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of &quot;wanting, but not being able, to participate in an activity that fulfills you.&quot;
He states that the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person does not do something but wants to do it.
Point out that with apathy there is no desire to do something.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is &quot;the alteration of the attention process, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time passes slowly.&quot;
Boredom can sound terrifyingly like depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that, although they may be related, people who are bored tend to see the problem as a matter of the environment or the world, while people who are depressed see the problem as themselves.
Sometimes we think we are bored, when what really happens to us is that we have trouble concentrating.
In their study &quot;The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention,&quot; published in the September issue of the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues referred to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape. of a person reading a magazine article.
Some groups listened to an unrelated television program at full volume in the next room, others listened to it at low volume so that it was barely perceptible, while the third group did not hear the audio at any time.
The group that listened to the program at low volume showed more boredom than the other two groups; They had trouble concentrating, but they weren&#39;t sure why and attributed it to boredom.
&quot;When you&#39;re trying to focus on a difficult or interesting task, impaired attention can lead to boredom,&quot; said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the study&#39;s authors.
&quot;On the other hand, when you&#39;re doing something boring, like spotting faulty parts on a manufacturing line, distracting music can help keep you from getting bored.&quot;
&quot;In fact, we now know that moving around or scribbling, actions that are often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can actually help combat boredom by making that person more physically alert.&quot;
&quot;Research shows that children who are allowed to move learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to be still,&quot; says Professor Fenske.
We all know what it&#39;s like to be bored at some point: a late plane, a monotonous speaker, an especially boring movie.
But some people are more prone to boredom than others.
To help measure it, some researchers developed a &quot;boredom tendency scale&quot; in the 1980s.
The scale includes questions like &quot;many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous&quot; and &quot;there are so many things that interest me that I don&#39;t have time to do everything.&quot;
Stephen Vodanovich, Professor of Psychology at the University of West Florida, says that, using these scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to get bored more often than girls, and specifically need more and more varied external stimulation.
But, in general, teenagers are a type of group that gets bored quite easily.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of Human and Community Development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day using a pager.
It found that 32 percent of teens said they were bored while in school or doing homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when not in school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether current boredom rates, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he said that what he did know was that &quot;adolescence is a time when boredom reaches its highest levels,&quot; in large part because both children and adolescents are not given much control over what what do you want to do.
So, back to my question from the beginning: is it good to be bored?
Sometimes it is not, since, taken to the extreme, it can expose us to absurd physical risks, such as placing bets or indulging in substance use as a method to combat it, as research shows.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers speak of the connection between boredom and creativity, according to Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying this question for more than two decades.
&quot;Boredom is the brain&#39;s way of telling you that you should be doing something else,&quot; says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
But the brain does not always know what is most appropriate.
If you are bored and use that energy to play guitar or cook, that will satisfy you.
But if you watch TV, it may satisfy you in the short term, but not in the long term.
&quot;So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he may no longer be bored, but he will not have learned to entertain himself or to dose,&quot; says Professor Fenske.
And &quot;that ability to dose applies to other situations,&quot; he says.
Your child not only learns to entertain himself, he learns to control himself better in other areas.
I don&#39;t think we really want to praise boredom.
But we shouldn&#39;t be too critical of him either.
Rather, our goal should be to feel comfortable away from the constant buzz of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
&quot;In our view, we need to be more bored, but boredom is too distressing and disturbing a desire to be related to anything worthwhile,&quot; he says.
He points out that what people are really looking for is a way to unwind and enjoy some downtime.
&quot;In an environment where we are constantly overstimulated,&quot; he says, &quot;it is difficult to find ways to focus our attention when the noise stops.&quot;
