Would I be forced to meet like-minded people only after dark?
Should I go Labor and suppress my natural tendencies?
The three years that awaited me were presented as a purgatory of ostracism and isolation.
The only openly Tory professor was Norman Stone, Professor of Contemporary History stationed at my college.
They hated him for being not only from the Conservative party, but also Thatcher&#39;s foreign policy adviser and one of the people who wrote her speeches to him.
He was hardly around.
He detested the place because it considered it provincial and insignificant and because of its adherence to the Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University, Ankara, Turkey.
&quot;You are not going to be happy here,&quot; he told me.
I began to commute daily from Oxford to my parents&#39; house in London, finding refuge with my more open metropolitan-minded family and friends.
I told my father that I hated Oxford and why.
He did not believe me.
When he was studying there in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
&quot;But it is the best place in the world,&quot; he said sadly.
&quot;They would never do that, not there among my beloved dream spiers.
Even my communist friends always had an impeccable attitude. &quot;
His aching eyes began to cloud.
&quot;Give it another chance.
I&#39;m sure they did it just to joke.
It would break my heart if you left it. &quot;
Exhausted from so many trips to London, my emotional stamina was deteriorating.
A friend of mine, who also supported the Conservative Party, had succumbed to pressure and renounced his creed.
The following week, during a seminar in which another history professor had hinted, in complete seriousness, that I was an &quot;enemy of the people,&quot; I decided to do the same.
Red with shame inside, I admitted that my parents had &quot;brainwashed&quot; me and called them &quot;stupid old men.&quot;
The truce was short-lived.
It was my father who put the last nail in the coffin of my college career at Oxford.
At that time my father wrote two weekly columns in the Murdoch press.
My door was locked.
I was huddled inside in fear and, after five minutes, my pursuers gave up.
When they left I packed my bag and caught the first train to London.
