The toughest job in the world: Kawah Ijen&#39;s human mules
For four euros, the porters of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through steep stone paths
There are people for whom their work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of 400 miners who make a living by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it has to go down every day to the bottom of its crater, where the sulfurous gas that emanates from the bowels of the Earth solidifies when it comes into contact with the air.
After uprooting large sulfur rocks, weighing about 70 kilograms in total, he carries them in two bamboo baskets that he carries on his shoulders through steep stone paths.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters of altitude, but the exhausted porters take more than 40 minutes to ascend at a snail&#39;s pace, keeping their balance and carefully measuring their steps so as not to slip and fall. the cliff.
They know that any misstep could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell down the cliffs of Kawah Ijen years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 euro cents for every kilo of sulfur they extract
Once at the top, they make their way through the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, wearily carrying the heavy baskets, they walk three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has placed a little lower, at 1,850 meters high.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, never better said, its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for every kilo of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even to bleach sugar.
&quot;As the normal thing is to carry 70 kilos, we take out about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip,&quot; explains Anto, who usually carries out three shipments a day.
It takes three hours each and ends up being ground, but they allow you to raise 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems a pittance for such an inhuman effort, it is triple what he would earn on the field.
&quot;The miners&#39; wage is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid at 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros)&quot;, clarifies the porter, who previously worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the cut was not that hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a compelling reason that, in Indonesia, It is as forceful as sulfur: &quot;I married a young woman from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I have brought her to Java to convert to Islam.&quot;
Anto has asthma, is breathing heavily, coughing constantly, and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At 27, Anto has been playing his skin for three years at Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already begun to take its toll despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, is breathing hard, coughs constantly, and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases released by the volcano.
It is the price you must pay to achieve your dream.
&quot;I will work two more years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French,&quot; he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished for life, this charming and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or hotel receptionist, but instead does the work of a mule.
Sharing a filthy wooden cabin with other porters, he gets up every day at two in the morning because the sulfur does not stop flowing at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and glows in the dark.
Defying the shadows, Anto descends into the crater, shining a small flashlight attached to his helmet, which he himself has bought with his money.
About 400 porters carry the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater
Despite its huge profits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulfur to save costs nor does it supply any equipment to the porters, who are already working on their own account.
In fact, they do not even see part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) camera surcharge that, together with the 15,000 rupee (1.2 euros) entry, the rangers of this natural park charge tourists who come to visit. photograph the volcano and its human mules.
&quot;This job is for beasts and not for people,&quot; protests Madrusin, a burly 42-year-old porter who has been at Kawah Ijen for three decades, since he left school.
Able to lift up to 110 kilos, he assures that he will endure working &quot;as long as he can&quot; because he needs the money to educate his three children, between 18 and 10 years old.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although the sulfur burns the throat and stings the eyes when the wind suddenly changes and traps the miners in the thick columns that come out of the volcano, they are so hard that no one complains of suffering serious diseases ... beyond, of course, of his usual respiratory problems, osteoarthritis, knee pain and shoulder sores, which have been deformed by the weight of the baskets.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unainik can already only carry 50 kilos at 53 years old.
Every day, he and his colleagues remove 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away along a goat path through the undergrowth.
&quot;I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life,&quot; proclaims Unainik, opening his mouth wide, where several teeth are missing.
Of her five children, the oldest, 30, also works carrying sulfur.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the toughest jobs in the world: that of the human mules of the Kawah Ijen.
Singapore seeks babies to save economy
Singaporeans blame career, stress, and the cost of property and education for not having children.
&quot;Singapore&#39;s population needs to grow.&quot;
I am a patriotic husband, you are my patriotic wife, let&#39;s do our civic duty and create life!
It may seem implausible that these verses are part of a peppermint ad, but despite that - or perhaps because of it - the video went viral on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The phrases are part of a rap that uses local references such as &quot;Let&#39;s put a bao (bun) in the oven&quot; to laugh at Singapore&#39;s birth rate.
The advertising company that made the video, BBH, hopes that the ad will bring attention to the problem in a fun way.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the power of music to get people to fulfill &quot;their national duty.&quot;
This is purely internet stuff, so we had to make it fun and funny.
It is the biggest problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world at reproducing ourselves, so we felt that this was an issue we had to address.
We knew that the government had tried many things, such as launching perfumes with pheromones or organizing speed-dating evenings.
Many of those ideas may have been creative, but they didn&#39;t necessarily work.
So we thought, why don&#39;t we get as creative as possible to solve this problem, which is to write a rap?
1.2 children
The one that doesn&#39;t take it so lightly is the Singaporean government.
It spends $ 1,300 a year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for married couples and parents grants up to $ 15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all of this has had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and strict social controls.
Singapore&#39;s birth rate, according to its national population division, currently stands at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2 - known as the replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why don&#39;t Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of Marriage and Family Policy at the National Population Division, says it is due to &quot;better education&quot; and &quot;a wider range of career opportunities.&quot;
&quot;That has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond getting married and starting a family,&quot; he explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to the rise in singleness, and to a delay in marriage and births, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at dramatically increasing immigration to cope with the declining population has created resentment among the local population.
There are websites in Singapore where barely disguised xenophobia is rife against many new immigrants, particularly the Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and not integrating.
Rising immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore&#39;s ruling party experienced its worst electoral result since independence last year.
Since the elections there has been an attempt to correct the problem, with higher fees and charges for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the drop in the birth rate has known effects on a nation&#39;s economic growth, tax revenues, healthcare costs, and immigration policies, the Singapore example is also having some unexpected consequences.
The government tries not to build so many small houses.
For example, it has started to affect the real estate sector.
The urban development authority has come to control the number of small apartments, known as &quot;shoe boxes&quot;, that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and have been very successful in sales.
However, there are concerns that they may promote a single lifestyle and discourage developers who want to build large, family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of real estate company EL Developers, says his &quot;shoe boxes&quot; sell much faster than larger units.
They are more popular, in the sense that units sell out for days, even weeks, faster than larger units.
This makes it much better for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new rules provide clearer guidance for developers, who were previously hampered if they wanted to offer too many small units in a project.
Too stressed
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new rules may be a step toward increasing the national birth rate, speaking to Singaporeans who work in the downtown financial district it appears that they will not have much of an effect.
&quot;People are very stressed, houses are expensive and so is education, so many people are putting it off,&quot; says a young executive.
Other people may have children.
&quot;But for me it is important to have my own money and time,&quot; says another young man in his 20s.
Men and women cite their careers, stress, and the cost of property and education as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So as much as the government tries to push its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, Singaporeans have the last word.
The private off line is private on line
Privacy.
According to the Dictionary of the Royal Spanish Academy, it is about the quality of private or &quot;the area of private life that has the right to protect from any interference&quot;.
What is private for a minor under 16 years of age?
How do you apply this definition in your daily life and on social media?
