&quot;Also that they are selective when what matters most to them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences,&quot; he adds.
According to the specialist, the most effective way to teach what privacy is to children and adolescents is through questions that make them reflect.
&quot;Telling them not to do it is useless,&quot; he adds.
Next, Porras lists some options: There are things that you would not tell a stranger, why do you do it on the Internet?
Or, would you like them to post a photo of you like the one you posted from a friend?
Do you know what the others post about you?
When you tag party photos, did you ask other people for permission to tag them?
And one more, does everyone need to know what you are doing every moment?
Another point is to make them see that they must act online as they do offline.
They are the same rules.
&quot;One outside the Internet acts with respect, morality and other principles, the same should be in social networks,&quot; he says.
Surveillance
Estuardo Guardia, university professor, primary school teacher and educational consultant, comments that it is essential that parents read social media policies thoroughly.
By understanding each of the items they have a solid foundation to discuss with their children about the implications of opening an account on the Internet.
