Unasur Summit ends without making the Lima Declaration public
The VI Presidential Summit of the South American Union of Nations (Unasur) concluded today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, previously announced and theoretically signed by the seven presidents in attendance.
Efe repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but sources from the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency indicated at the beginning that they were going to hand it over after the closing, but later they affirmed that in at some point it will be published on the Peruvian government website.
When consulted for the text, they indicated that the content had been exposed by the president of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Journalists&#39; access to information on the Summit was restricted at all times.
During the day, only the video without sound of the presidential assembly with the message &quot;private session, restricted audio&quot; was broadcast in the press room.
The little information that circulated among the reporters was delivered by the press spokesmen of some of the Unasur governments attending the meeting, although not the Peruvian.
The only document released during the day was the list of assisting presidents, which caused the discomfort of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Subsequently, the Presidency of Peru sent an email to the media with the &quot;final declaration&quot; of the summit, but it is Humala&#39;s pronouncement, and not the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru was the host of the III South America-Arab Countries Summit (ASPA), and on that occasion, despite being insistently requested by the press, the so-called Declaration of Lima that they had previously announced was not disseminated either.
On the official ASPA website, it can be confirmed that the document was published last Tuesday.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities made an effort to ensure that there were secure transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited the obtaining of information as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept a ruling from the Court of The Hague to settle a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and of Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and ratified that they will respect the decision of the (ICJ), which begins on Monday in The Hague to hear the arguments of both parties, in the process that Lima presented against Santiago.
&quot;We will abide by and execute the sentence that defines the differences that we are bringing to this international court today,&quot; said Humala, along with his Chilean counterpart.
&quot;Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country that respects international law, the peaceful solution of disputes, international treaties and tribunals,&quot; added Piñera, and greeted Humala with a handshake, along with to the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation of both presidents that they will submit to the ICJ occurred after Colombia denounced this week the Pact of Bogotá by which it had agreed to submit to the rulings of that international court, after a decision on maritime limits with Nicaragua that it considered seriously erroneous .
The summit was held with the absences of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the removal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was in charge of opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit, shortly after noon in Lima.
The president read the final document in which he reported that 16 agreements were adopted and the lines of action were set for 31 projects among South American countries for a total of 17 billion dollars in investments.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries will take &quot;important steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship, for which we are expanding the residency agreements.&quot;
He reported that actions are being promoted to improve &quot;cooperation in the fight against citizen insecurity and against transnational organized crime, actions to make medicines more accessible, access to the internet at low prices in all corners of South America, and provide joint and efficient risks of natural disasters &quot;.
With a Europe in crisis, &quot;the economic consolidation (of Latin America) should not have a triumphalist matrix but should serve to expand our productive matrix and envision a better future for our peoples,&quot; Humala added.
&quot;We have decided to privilege a group of 31 emblematic projects that will improve the connection of the spaces of South America, especially in rural and border areas ... uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits,&quot; said the Peruvian president in a message read.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five correspond to Peru, and are located in the transversal axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two point to a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give further details.
Likewise, the final document mentioned the political situation in Paraguay.
&quot;We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve for his reincorporation to the Union of South American Nations,&quot; from which he is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated, and of good relations between neighbors, was another of the issues highlighted by the summit.
In this sense, the president of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before beginning his participation in the regional meeting that he hoped to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to respectfully discuss the maritime dispute after a ruling of the ICJ, questioned by Bogotá.
&quot;Tomorrow (Saturday) I may have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega,&quot; Santos said.
&quot;We are going to review all these paths, they are not exclusive, even the treaty with Nicaragua will require a conversation with Nicaragua,&quot; he stressed.
&quot;With President Ortega, I hope I can tell him to handle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible,&quot; Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet in Mexico on Saturday where they plan to attend the inauguration of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Likewise, as part of the summit, the defense ministers of the bloc met previously to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defense matters in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay make up UNASUR, although the last country is suspended.
Peru holds the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
&quot;South America must learn from Europe to integrate a citizenship&quot;: Rafael Correa
The president of Ecuador, Rafael Correa, affirmed today that the creation of a common citizenship is a goal in which &quot;South America, in this case, must learn from Europe.&quot;
Correa, who participated in the VI Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur), held in Lima, declared to the state TV Peru that Europeans &quot;killed themselves in World War II&quot; and in other conflicts, &quot;but now they are practically a homeland. &quot;
In that sense, he defended the project of establishing South American citizenship that the member countries of Unasur encourage.
&quot;We must achieve the free mobility of citizens and workers through any South American country, as is already the case with the members of the Andean Community, but there are still reactionary sectors that want to return us to the past,&quot; he warned.
The Ecuadorian president was also in favor of the recomposition of the Organization of American States (OAS) under the premise of reducing the influence of the Anglo-Saxon states and taking into account those who have signed the San José pact on rights humans.
Those who teach never commit to anything and, on the other hand, we South Americans sign everything.
&quot;It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights is in Washington under the financing of the United States,&quot; he said, referring to the political asylum given by Ecuador to WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
Correa assured that he is not sorry for that decision because with it he has not betrayed his principles, but has respected his &quot;deep democratic and human rights values.&quot;
He added that, at the time, &quot;there were well-founded suspicions that Assange was extradited to a third country and his process was not respected.&quot;
He also criticized the Swedish courts for demanding that he submit to interrogation in their territory for an alleged sexual crime when &quot;Swedish law itself allows it to be done by videoconference, which could be done from the Ecuadorian embassy in London.&quot;
Correa said there is a risk that Assange&#39;s physical and mental health will deteriorate.
&quot;I have not spoken with him since he is in our embassy, but the ambassador informed me that he had a small lung problem, nothing serious,&quot; said the Ecuadorian president.
What there is is the danger that your physical and mental health will deteriorate from being locked in a small space without being able to exercise outdoors.
&quot;That complicates the health of any person,&quot; he added.
Correa pointed out that the solution to the asylum granted to Assange since June in the Ecuadorian embassy in London, through the granting of a safe conduct that allows him to travel to Ecuador, is in the hands of Great Britain, Sweden and the European legal authorities and stressed that there has been talks with London in search of a solution to the closure of the WikiLeaks founder.
We do not negotiate with human rights, we do not use that word in this case, but there have been permanent conversations.
&quot;The solution to this problem is in the hands of Great Britain, Sweden and the European legal authorities because Assange&#39;s lawyer, Baltazar Garzón, is doing a series of procedures in different European instances,&quot; he mentioned.
And he opined that &quot;if Great Britain gives the safe conduct tomorrow this will end.&quot;
And if Sweden, as perfectly permitted by its legislation and as it has done in other cases, interrogates Mr. Assange at the Ecuadorian embassy in London or interrogates him via Skype this problem will end tomorrow.
Correa took the opportunity to reaffirm himself as a defender of press freedom and clarified that what he does not tolerate is &quot;mediocrity, bad faith and lies, which undermine freedom of expression.&quot;
&quot;The greatest enemies of press freedom are not evil and perverse politicians but bad journalists based on profit, blackmail and extortion,&quot; he said.
In this regard, he congratulated himself that these journalists are no longer &quot;neither the bankers nor the hegemonic and bourgeois countries that dominate Ecuador,&quot; and he advanced that if re-elected &quot;he will deepen the revolution to continue on the right path and direction.&quot;
Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto of Paraguay in Unasur at least until its next elections, arguing that the body &quot;must be firm and not tolerate opportunism and coup-covered legalities&quot; because in reality &quot;it destroyed the legitimacy of Paraguayan democracy &quot;.
The Ecuadorian president also considered &quot;perfectly pertinent&quot; the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to now negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime limits between the two countries after the ruling of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which benefited the Nicaraguan maritime sovereignty.
At the moment this ruling is not being complied with.
It is a problem between a South American country and a Central American one.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the will to walk together.
They have to be processed broadly to overcome them and move on.
He also trusted in a good conclusion to the litigation over maritime limits that Peru and Chile maintain in the same court and said that &quot;it is correct for Latin America to seek international instances if the two countries agree to accept a ruling no matter how hard it may be.&quot;
In reference to the eventuality that he appears as a candidate in the next presidential elections in Ecuador to seek a third consecutive term, he said that he sees that possibility &quot;with great optimism and joy, although sometimes it is quite hard.&quot;
Correa assured that if he loses the February 2013 elections, he will retire from public life.
Personally, I have never been interested in power, but in situations as unjust as Ecuador&#39;s, that socioeconomic poverty can only be corrected from political power.
&quot;My political movement believed that it was I who guaranteed that probable victory, because we have to accept that responsibility,&quot; he said.
If I win, it would be my last term in office and from there we left public life.
If we lose the same.
&quot;It is a decision,&quot; he said.
Correa also referred to the new health treatment of Venezuelan President Hugo Chávez in Cuba.
I just spoke with Venezuelan Vice President Nicolás Maduro and he told me that he traveled to a treatment that was already planned, routine, that the campaign to return to Cuba was expected to pass.
&quot;It does not mean a relapse in the state of health of President Chávez,&quot; he commented.
