AIDS deaths today are cause of late detection
Fabrizio was 21 years old when his test result was confirmed: AIDS positive.
&quot;It was as if a bomb had dropped on me&quot;, he refers to recalling the moment of the announcement, which the doctor tried to make &quot;softer&quot;, without evident success.
The boy hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to learn about it; so hard that he already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is, without a doubt, one of the oldest patients in the HIV Unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), which he arrived in 1994 after several battles.
Fabrizio has lived with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something difficult to imagine in the early 1990s, when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigma.
So even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him &quot;because he had a cut.&quot;
So having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Now it is possible to survive this syndrome and do it with quality of life.
However, ignorant of their illness, many people still arrive when the virus has already wreaked havoc, &quot;depleted&quot; their immune systems, and they are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, at least of the first reported cases, &quot;the great achievement at this time means that the survival of a patient who starts treatment in a timely manner and the survival of the general population is exactly the same, &quot;said the head of the HCG HIV Unit, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, after referring that this information was endorsed in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectologist and expert in HIV / AIDS, Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists had concluded that AIDS was not a fatal sentence, but the years of survival and quality of life depend on the degree of damage to the immune system they present patients at the beginning of the diagnosis, with a better expectation for those who are not drug users: up to 30 years with a CD4 count of 200 and 50 years, when they report 500 CD4s.
In simple words, the above means that whoever receives a positive HIV diagnosis at 25 years of age, under these terms &quot;as long as they remain in control, they will be able to live without problems until they are 75 years old,&quot; explained the interviewee.
To measure this progress, it should be remembered that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years on average.
Although mortality has dropped significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying of AIDS fell from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNAIDS annual report), it is also true that since the appearance From AIDS, 60 percent of the patients in the national database have died.
Only in Jalisco 255 people died in 2011, and there are 187 deaths until May of this year; However, it is ensured that there is universal access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
- Why are there still deaths?
- It seems to me that the problem is not one of access to treatment.
This is how I envision it, this is how it has happened to us in our hospital.
At least in the last 12 years we have not had a shortage of medicine, the problem is that patients arrive very advanced because they do not know their state of infection, that is, in late stages of the disease.
He gave a conclusive fact: &quot;Nine out of ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection, what must be done to have a greater impact on global mortality is to make earlier diagnoses and, therefore, tests have to be offered. detection in a massive way, to all the people who require it &quot;.
In his proposal, specialists and officials of the State Council for the Prevention of AIDS in Jalisco (Coesida) coincide, as well as the patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who came to have the test in a private laboratory, only motivated because a friend had done it and, despite At his young age, he was already in the AIDS stage and even suffered from Kaposi&#39;s sarcoma, a cancerous tumor that is one of the common complications.
