Actor Larry Hagman dies
Larry Hagman, born on September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth (Texas), became world famous for his central role as John Ross Ewing, better known as &quot;JR&quot;., In the television series &quot;Dallas&quot;, in the who embodied an unscrupulous, malicious and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as predatory oil tycoon JR Ewing on the television series &quot;Dallas&quot; became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as JR in a new season of &quot;Dallas,&quot; died Friday afternoon of complications from cancer, according to a family statement provided to The Associated Press by the Warner Bros. production house. from &quot;Dallas&quot;.
&quot;Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, again playing the iconic role that he loved best,&quot; the family said.
Larry&#39;s family and his closest friends were with him in Dallas for the Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played the role of his wife in the original series and the sequel, was with Hagman when he passed away in a Dallas hospital, her publicist Jeffrey Lane said.
He brought joy to everyone he met.
He was creative, generous, funny, funny, loving, and talented, and I will miss him terribly.
&quot;He was an original person and lived life to the fullest,&quot; Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and acknowledged that he had been drinking heavily for years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was found in his liver and he underwent a transplant.
Years before &quot;Dallas,&quot; Hagman became famous on television as a decent guy in the light comedy &quot;I Dream of Jeannie,&quot; aired on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it he played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life is altered when he meets an attractive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and takes her to live with him at his home.
He was also the protagonist of two comedies that aired for a short time, &quot;The Good Life&quot; (NBC, 1971-72) and &quot;Here We Go Again&quot; (ABC, 1973).
His film work included critically acclaimed roles in &quot;The Group,&quot; &quot;Harry and Tonto&quot; and &quot;Primary Colors.&quot;
But it was his masterful portrayal of the charmingly obnoxious JR that led Hagman to his peak.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters in their orbit ran from April 1978 to May 1991.
The promotional phrase &quot;Who shot JR?&quot;, Thought to generate expectation around an episode full of emotions in which the character of Hagman was almost assassinated, generated international speculation and millions of dollars risked in gambling houses.
It also helped give the series a record viewership at the time.
When the answer was revealed in a November 1980 episode, an average of 41 million viewers tuned in and made &quot;Dallas&quot; the second-most-watched entertainment program in history, behind the end of &quot;MASH&quot; in 1983. which had 50 million viewers.
It was JR&#39;s sister-in-law, Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
JR got her pregnant and then threatened to brand her as a prostitute unless she left town, but others also had reason to attack him.
Hagman portrayed Ewing as an insatiable crook with a charismatic smile: a cheating businessman and cheating husband who tried to get his alcoholic wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), into a hospital.
&quot;I know what I want on JR&#39;s headstone,&quot; Hagman said in 1988.
It should say, &quot;Here lies honest citizen JR Ewing.&quot;
This is the only deal that lost.
Original series co-star Victoria Principal remembered Hagman on Friday as &quot;huge, on and off the screen.&quot;
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of each one of us, that we were lucky enough to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of &quot;Dallas&quot; were broadcast a few months ago with great success for the TNT channel.
The recording of five of the chapters for the second season had already finished and a sixth was in process, the network reported.
There was no immediate statement from Warner or TNT on how the series will handle the loss of Hagman.
