They begin a course that explores the &quot;End of the world&quot;
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to teach a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible hook: The end of the &quot;long countdown&quot; of the Mayan Calendar, on December 21, which has been clung to many people as proof that the end of the world is coming.
But Charmé had no idea what to expect in the next couple of months: The cataclysmic Hurricane Sandy, a fiscal cliff some have called &quot;debt rmageddon&quot; and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where Christian theorists of the end of the times believe that the Apocalypse will begin.
&quot;I didn&#39;t realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester there has ever been,&quot; Charmé told students at Rutgers-Camden University (NJ) this week.
If you analyze what has been happening in the world today as if we were 30 days away and counting, this has been a really good period.
And remember that bad is good for those with the apocalyptic mindset.
And he is not the only professor offering courses on the &quot;end of the world&quot; this semester, in theory the last in history.
At Temple, Adjunct Professor Barry Vacker is teaching &quot;Media, Culture, and the End of the World.&quot;
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
&quot;We look at why these ideas proliferate over time,&quot; he said, and how they offer what-if scenarios that guide certain human behavior.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month students analyzed apocalyptic-themed movies and explored how they compare to real-life examples.
&quot;I have tried to inform students about what is possible, probable, credible and impossible,&quot; Vacker said.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an adjunct professor of Art History and Anthropology, have teamed up to teach a course, titled only &quot;The End of the World. &quot;.
&quot;We didn&#39;t add &#39;2012&#39; to always have the option to teach the course again, in case the world doesn&#39;t end,&quot; Restall said.
Despite the &quot;impending doom,&quot; students must study, generate projects, and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will be taken on the eve of the apocalypse, leaving students with no choice but to work &quot;until the very night the world is supposed to end,&quot; Restall said.
The courses were quite popular.
&quot;It was saturated in two hours,&quot; Restall said of his high GPA course, which was filled with 35 students.
